The '''Aye Formation''' is a [[geologic formation]] in the Dinant [[Synclinorium]], [[Belgium]]. It is part of the Condroz Group,<ref name="Condroz">{{cite web | url=http://ncs.naturalsciences.be/devonian/42-descriptions | title=Devonian—Descriptions | publisher=National Commission for Stratigraphy Belgium | work=Devonian | accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> at the base of the middle [[Famennian]] (Upper [[Devonian]]). It is characterized by the presence of a [[conodont]] fossil ''[[Palmatolepis]] rhomboidea''.<ref name="StratBelg">{{cite web | url=http://ncs.naturalsciences.be/devonian/427-aye-formation-aye | title=Aye Formation | publisher=National Commission for Stratigraphy Belgium | work=Devonian | accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>
It is composed mostly of greenish [[shale]]s and [[siltstone]]s with some lenses of [[sandstone]]. As it formed in an offshore position, in a subtidal wave-influenced environment, [[bioturbation]] features are significant. [[Cross-bedding]] structures also occur.<ref name="StratBelg" />
The [[stratotype]] is located in the area of [[Houyet]] and [[Aye (village)|Aye]] in Belgium.<ref name="StratBelg" />
