{{Politics of Burundi}}
Indirect '''presidential elections''' were held in [[Burundi]] on 19 August 2005.<ref>[http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/burundi-2005-presidential-election-results Burundi: 2005 Presidential election results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109153218/http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/burundi-2005-presidential-election-results |date=January 9, 2015 }} EISA</ref> Members of the [[National Assembly (Burundi)|National Assembly]] and [[Senate (Burundi)|Senate]] chose the new president of the republic for a five-year term. The sole candidate, [[Pierre Nkurunziza]] of the [[National Council for the Defense of Democracy – Forces for the Defense of Democracy|CNDD–FDD]], was elected by a vote of 151–9.<ref>[http://www.electionguide.org/digest/post/12019/ Burundi Announces Presidential Election Results] IFES</ref> Nkurunziza was sworn in on 26 August 2005.<ref>[http://uca.edu/politicalscience/dadm-project/sub-saharan-africa-region/burundi-1962-present/ 43. Burundi (1962-present)] University of Central Arkansas</ref>
==Electoral system== The election was held using the multiple round system. In order to win in the first round of voting, Nkurunziza was required to receive at least two-thirds of the vote (108 votes).<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/report/55922/burundi-parliament-elects-nkurunziza-nation-s-president Burundi: Parliament elects Nkurunziza nation's president] IRIN, 19 August 2005</ref>
