{{Shia Islam}}

'''Shia Islam in Algeria''' is composed of minority [[Shia Islam|Shia Muslim]] community of [[Algeria]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunni and Shia: The Worlds of Islam|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/wideangle/episodes/pilgrimage-to-karbala/sunni-and-shia-the-worlds-of-islam/1737/|accessdate=30 July 2013|date=26 March 2007}}</ref>{{better source|date=May 2017}}

==History and culture==
Traditionally, there have been very few Shias in Algeria, except for those who were around in the [[Middle Ages]], although there are a few native Shias and some converts. Western Algeria was part of Zaydi Shia [[Idrisid dynasty]] state when [[Idris II of Morocco|Idris II]] died in 828 CE.<ref>{{cite web|title=Idrisid Dynasty|url=http://www.britannica.com/topic/Idrisid-dynasty#ref176944|website=Encyclopædia Britannica|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> The Ismaili Shia [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimid]] state originated among the [[Kutama]] people of Algeria. The dynasty was founded in 909 CE by [[Abdullah al-Mahdi Billah]], who in the late 9th century started a movement among the Kutama [[Berbers]] and managed to convert them to Shia [[Islam]]. In the Middle Ages local [[Berbers|Berber]] dynasties adopted Shia Islam.<ref>{{cite book|title=The agony of Algeria|year=1997|publisher=C. Hurst & Co. Publishers|location=London|isbn=1850651779|page=145|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zKLHw5AzJm4C&dq=shia+islam+in+algeria&source=gbs_navlinks_s|author=Martin Stone|edition=illustrated|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> According to Shia sources recently, the region has allegedly seen an increasing popular interest in [[Shia Islam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mazhab-i-Ahl`ol Bayt (p) spreading increasingly in Algeria|url=http://www.jafariyanews.com/2k5_news/nov/29shiites_algeria.htm|accessdate=30 July 2013|newspaper=Jafariya News Network|date=29 November 2005|author=Sultan Ahmed|location=ALGIERS, Algeria}}</ref>

The following Shia Muslim observances are commemorated in Algeria:<ref>{{cite web|title=Algeria 's National Holidays and other National Celebrations|url=http://africa.world-towns.net/subcontinent/national-events.asp?GetCID=1000000058|accessdate=1 August 2013|date=17 September 2012<!-- 09:09:15-->}}</ref>
* ''[[Arba'een]]'' of [[Husayn ibn Ali|Imam Hussain]]
* [[Mawlid|''Mawlid an Nabi'']], the birth of the [[Muhammad|Prophet Muhammad]]
* Birth of [[Muhammad al-Mahdi|Imam Mahdi]]
* ''Eid al-Ghadeer'', commemorates the appointment of Imam Ali ibn Abi Talib by Prophet [[Muhammad]] as his immediate successor

==Population estimates==
The Shia population of [[Algeria]] is estimated to be between one half to two percent of the total Muslim population of Algeria.{{fact|date=May 2017}} According to [[Pew Research Center|Pew Forum]], it is less than one percent<ref>{{cite web|title=Estimated Percentage Range of Shia by Country|url=http://www.pewforum.org/uploadedfiles/Orphan_Migrated_Content/Shiarange.pdf|publisher=Pew forum|accessdate=30 July 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801221118/http://www.pewforum.org/uploadedfiles/Orphan_Migrated_Content/Shiarange.pdf|archivedate=1 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> while as per Imam Husayn (as) Encyclopedia the population of Shia in Algeria is around two percent of the total Muslim population of Algeria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shia Population in: Algeria|url=http://www.ahl-ul-bayt.org/en.php/page,3100A8779.html|publisher=The AhlulBayt World Assembly|accessdate=1 August 2013|date=8 April 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606204426/http://www.ahl-ul-bayt.org/en.php/page,3100A8779.html|archivedate=6 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

